02:25.193 --> 02:28.399
year leave of absence from Duke. to serve as a 
so-called liaison scientist in oceanography and

02:29.155 --> 02:34.762
marine biology, ONR London. And at that time, I was 
officially a civilian employee of the Department

02:36.444 --> 02:42.111
of the Navy. And what exactly does a liaison 
officer in London, let's say, do in terms of advice

02:43.332 --> 02:50.601
to ONR? Well, the primary objective was to visit as 
many marine oceanographic facilities as

02:50.621 --> 02:57.610
possible in Europe. Talk with people about trends 
in research. And then on your return to London,

03:03.706 --> 03:17.102
write up an article for what's known as European 
Scientific Notes, published monthly by the

03:03.706 --> 03:17.102
London office, distributed to over maybe 3,000 
people in the United States. And the articles that

03:18.624 --> 03:28.255
you write give an impression of the laboratories 
that you visit, the programs that are there, the

03:18.624 --> 03:28.255
facilities they have for research. ever interest 
they may have on having American scientists work

03:28.471 --> 03:32.316
there. Indications of an interest in cooperative 
research. So it's to primarily keep the U.S.

03:37.883 --> 03:45.413
scientific community informed on trends in 
Europe. Has there traditionally always been one

03:46.355 --> 03:51.702
American scientist attached to the ONR in London? 
Oh, at the time I was there, there were About 35.

03:56.208 --> 03:56.729
About 35. And 17 of them were civilians 
representing not just oceanography. They go

04:01.774 --> 04:04.897
everything from anthropology to zoology. And the 
other 17 were blue suitors, so-called, line Navy

04:05.778 --> 04:15.549
officers who had a more applied mission-oriented 
interest, but it was the same sort of thing. They

04:16.470 --> 04:24.398
would visit the admiralty office or admiralty 
labs or French or Western German

04:27.652 --> 04:28.313
the academic.

04:32.458 --> 04:38.485
Has this been your primary connection with ONR, 
then your tour of duty, so to speak, in London? Oh,

04:39.586 --> 04:40.547
yeah. I've always had a reasonably close contact 
since the old days of Sid Gallop. Sid was in charge

04:45.212 --> 04:56.005
of oceanic biology, ONR, Washington for many 
years, and I think got me started on my

04:45.212 --> 04:56.005
international interest. Okay, that's the point 
I'm trying to move us to. You're deeply involved

05:00.976 --> 05:12.292
all through your career with international 
organizations, and that seems to be the striking

05:00.976 --> 05:12.292
point about your career in terms of sitting in the 
Senate. How do you explain that? How did that

05:13.594 --> 05:14.455
happen? Well, I remember the phone conversation. 
In 1957, I received a formal invitation from

05:17.439 --> 05:25.030
Professor Crisp, now a fellow of the Royal 
Society, then director of a small lab at Bangor,

05:25.668 --> 05:42.148
Wales, inviting me to present a paper at the 15th 
International Congress of Zoology in a section

05:25.668 --> 05:42.148
that was devoted to barnacles and celebrating the 
Darwin Centennial. I was then just barely out of

05:43.570 --> 05:53.262
graduate school, and of course it came as quite a 
thrill, but the sad part of it was I didn't have a

05:43.570 --> 05:53.262
cent. So, nothing ventured, nothing gained. I 
called O&R Washington.

06:08.984 --> 06:09.505
You can turn it off again. Sure. Didn't have any 
money. Right. What is happening is that you have no

06:11.527 --> 06:15.492
money and you said nothing ventured, nothing 
gained. Right. Which I mean, I assume you called

06:15.913 --> 06:17.415
O&R. So I called Sid Gower, who I knew casually, and 
told him about the invitations. and asked if it

06:23.077 --> 06:28.247
would be possible to get some financial support 
through ONR to permit me to participate. And Sid

06:29.610 --> 06:38.347
indicated that under one primary condition, and 
that would be that I would not be permitted to go

06:29.610 --> 06:38.347
directly to London in return. I would have to agree 
to visit at least one British marine laboratory.

06:44.474 --> 06:48.558
which, of course, was ridiculous because I would 
have given my ITs to visit several. So I

06:49.338 --> 06:57.046
reluctantly accepted the conditions, and he 
provided me with what was then known as Military

06:49.338 --> 06:57.046
Air Transportation Service travel. And that got 
me started in the London meeting where I met all

06:58.587 --> 07:10.838
sorts of people from all over the world, visited 
the Scottish Marine Biological Laboratory

06:58.587 --> 07:10.838
afterwards in Oban. Well, it's now in Oban. It used 
to be in Millport. Then went down to the big marine

07:13.432 --> 07:18.680
biological lab in Plymouth, met a lot of that 
crowd. So when I came home, I had started to become

07:19.000 --> 07:25.690
familiar with a number of European scientists. 
And it just seems to have continued, the contacts

07:26.752 --> 07:32.300
that I made then.

