international organizations will play a role 
later on and then trying to renegotiate

10:33.822 --> 10:57.518
activities of let's say physical and geological 
oceanography Oh, I'm sure that there will be a long

10:57.970 --> 11:04.900
progression, just as there has been already in the 
Law of the Sea discussions that will go on ad

10:57.970 --> 11:04.900
nauseum. Now, how did you become connected with 
the NSF programs in India?

11:15.236 --> 11:17.379
Through O&R London.

11:24.209 --> 11:27.454
While I was there as a liaison scientist, the 
captain wanted someone to go to Delhi for a

11:28.463 --> 11:32.447
meeting. And somehow I fell into that slot. So I 
went. And then two months later, the captain

11:37.733 --> 11:50.386
wanted someone who was an expert on India to take 
three Washington VIPs on a tour of marine

11:37.733 --> 11:50.386
facilities in India. Since I was the only member of 
the staff that had ever been anywhere in India, I

11:50.867 --> 11:55.652
was the expert. And on that second tour, I met some 
number of Indian scientists and got to know them

11:56.594 --> 12:03.182
and communicated with them. The whole thing 
evolved from that contact. And when NSF wanted

12:08.169 --> 12:13.255
somebody to go over there for several things, they 
asked me if I would go. Since I knew the people, I

12:13.516 --> 12:14.797
went. Is marine biology making significant 
strides in that part of the world?

12:22.848 --> 12:24.610
I wouldn't say significant, no. Of course, it's 
been several years and the whole political

12:26.243 --> 12:30.449
climate there has changed since I was there. It 
could, but there are some number of traditions

12:30.509 --> 12:43.808
that are going to have to be broken down before 
there's much really achieved. In your opinion,

12:45.651 --> 12:54.023
will international cooperation, as you conceive 
of it, bring direct aid to underdeveloped

12:45.651 --> 12:54.023
countries?

12:56.551 --> 12:57.192
such as India?

13:00.956 --> 13:04.040
Only if the political climate of the country 
encourages it. And the reason I qualify that,

13:04.701 --> 13:11.269
there has been a so-called PL-480 program in India 
for 20 years. And the Indian politicians are very

13:12.791 --> 13:23.664
reluctant to give it free reign because of what 
they feel would be a threat to the economy plus a

13:12.791 --> 13:23.664
threat to their jurisdiction. Now, who sponsors 
the PL-480 program? Oh, it's like a piece of pie

13:26.960 --> 13:33.368
that is cut up by some number of different U.S. 
agencies. EPA, NOAA, ONR, NSF, AID, the Congress.

13:43.461 --> 13:43.641
Okay. And I somehow or another have you contacted 
with, or you connected with the PL-480 program and

13:44.362 --> 13:52.092
the Smithsonian Institution at the same time. Is 
that possible? Oh yeah, because the Smithsonian

13:52.953 --> 13:55.296
has a piece of the pie. Okay, and what was your 
relationship with the Smithsonian and PL-480?

13:58.796 --> 14:14.871
Okay, the Smithsonian ran its PL-480 programs in a 
rather unique way, in that they set up an advisory

13:58.796 --> 14:14.871
committee of scientists, one for biological 
sciences, and I happened to serve on that

13:58.796 --> 14:14.871
committee for about three years. And they insist 
that on any excess currency program, there must be

14:16.268 --> 14:26.259
a U.S. scientist as a counterpart to the scientist 
from that country. So it's not just an effort to

14:27.340 --> 14:39.053
provide financial support to the scientist of 
some country, but it's to try to tie it to the U.S.

14:27.340 --> 14:39.053
scientific community. but through my 
involvement with their biological advisory

14:39.674 --> 14:50.310
committee and visiting some number of their 
facilities and programs, I got rather

14:39.674 --> 14:50.310
knowledgeable. And exactly what would you do in 
terms of your activities with PL-480?

14:57.020 --> 14:58.863
Smithsonian. We would review proposals that had 
been submitted by U.S. scientists, usually with

14:59.123 --> 15:09.158
the scientists from one of the other PL-480 
countries, and then either recommend that it be

15:10.454 --> 15:17.363
funded or recommend that it not be funded or 
recommend that it be modified and reconsidered.

15:19.085 --> 15:19.225
Okay. And

15:19.245 --> 15:28.357
in your opinion, what countries seem to work the 
best in the PL-480 program?

15:32.122 --> 15:36.468
Well, the Yugoslavs had a very efficient program 
going. Israel undoubtedly would be the top of the

15:37.629 --> 15:40.393
list. But it was not really a, they had an advantage 
in that many of their scientists are trained in

15:41.588 --> 15:47.138
this country. They speak English almost as well as 
they do their own language. They have a lot of

15:51.406 --> 15:56.816
traditions and customs which are common to this 
country. So they started out from a much closer

15:57.016 --> 16:05.892
working base than someone, say, in India

15:57.016 --> 16:05.892
would. or would you venture to compare, for 
example, scientific programs overseas and

16:07.289 --> 16:14.678
scientific programs in the United States? Yeah, 
it's possible.

16:21.947 --> 16:29.235
If you start out with, say, West Germany, their 
level of science is very similar to ours. England,

16:30.457 --> 16:35.743
depending on the discipline, now if we're talking 
about oceanography,

16:37.276 --> 16:42.424
Some of their oceanographic programs are 
certainly equal to the better ones in this

16:37.276 --> 16:42.424
country. Then you begin to get into a pretty gray 
area. France, there's a lot more exception there.

16:51.499 --> 16:53.262
Italy, there's still more exception. The 
Scandinavian countries in certain specific

16:54.183 --> 17:00.894
subdivisions of the discipline, they're easily 
equal to us. Others, they may not be. Soviet Union,

17:04.546 --> 17:09.731
in certain specific areas, they are equal to us. In 
others, they're about where we were in the early

17:11.172 --> 17:13.675
30s. And once you've covered those countries, and 
I can't speak to East Germany because I've never

17:15.116 --> 17:33.473
been there, but then you begin to get into a whole 
third tier of countries where they don't really

17:15.116 --> 17:33.473
have a very well-organized or a very modern 
oceanographic program.

17:36.254 --> 17:37.816
is another story entirely. Japan, very possibly 
in the realm of especially fisheries, would

17:39.418 --> 17:46.608
easily be equal to us, but in pure oceanography, 
no. It has seemed, and I certainly can stand to be

17:49.032 --> 18:04.573
corrected on this, it has seemed that the ONR gave a 
great deal of direction to our beginnings as a

17:49.032 --> 18:04.573
country in oceanography, in formal oceanography 
after World War II. Do you feel that ONR still gives

18:04.942 --> 18:07.925
that kind of direction?

18:10.688 --> 18:13.050
Well, I couldn't agree more with your first 
statement. There's no doubt in my mind that we owe

18:13.130 --> 18:24.141
the early development, the period of 45-50, the 
early development of oceanography almost

18:13.130 --> 18:24.141
exclusively to ONR. Then, with the birth of NSF, 
some of the role of ONR was taken over. And I'm sure

18:31.148 --> 18:39.702
others have commented that many of the staff who 
had been in ONR went with NSF. And then, of course,

18:39.722 --> 18:51.743
later you had the birth of some number of other 
granting agencies, and AEC began to take over some

18:39.722 --> 18:51.743
minor role, now more major, in coastal 
oceanography. Eventually you had NOAA. But NOAA

18:56.242 --> 19:05.596
has never assumed any of the role that ONR had in the 
sense of support of oceanography through grants.

19:05.616 --> 19:08.800
They've tried to do it in-house with varying 
degrees of success.

19:11.444 --> 19:22.320
So the role has been diversified, and many of the 
things that ONR did in the 45-50 period are now done

19:11.444 --> 19:22.320
by other people, but not necessarily any more 
efficiently. Do you think the diversification

19:22.661 --> 19:24.223
was a good thing?

19:30.127 --> 19:52.887
Well, if you consider the emphasis which was put on 
ONR's support several years ago toward

19:30.127 --> 19:52.887
mission-oriented research, if that had happened 
without NSF being in existence, I think it would

19:30.127 --> 19:52.887
have been a real blow to basic oceanography. But 
the fact that NSF was available to pick up some of

19:54.088 --> 20:00.133
the pieces lessened the impact Diversification 
usually is pretty good if there's any real effort

20:00.772 --> 20:11.088
to coordinate and see to it that there's not too 
much duplication.

