together when I was a graduate student. barnacle

21:00.796 --> 21:03.280
shell development. And I became intrigued by the 
fact that you can't really study development of a

21:03.300 --> 21:13.294
shell unless you know the larval stages that 
contribute to the adult that grows the shell. And

21:13.314 --> 21:17.279
that led to a study of a number of aspects of 
crustacean development. So you could say yes. But

21:21.165 --> 21:23.308
there were a number of other people who influenced 
that. Good. I was going to say, who else would you

21:24.029 --> 21:30.398
consider big, as we see in history, during the 
1950s, shaping your career? One name stands out

21:30.479 --> 21:43.316
perhaps above all, and that's Gunnar Thorsen, who 
was the man who developed the laboratory at

21:30.479 --> 21:43.316
Elsinore following the Second World War. He was 
professor at Copenhagen. I came to know him quite

21:46.640 --> 21:47.962
well. He visited here some number of times, and his 
47th publication on the larval development of

21:48.622 --> 21:59.997
Danish marine bottom invertebrates became a 
Bible for me when I was a graduate student. And

22:00.702 --> 22:02.604
again, one of those crazy coincidences. My first 
semester at Duke, I was required, as were all

22:04.265 --> 22:14.334
graduate students, to give a report to my peers on 
some research publication. I thrashed around

22:15.355 --> 22:18.718
trying to find an appropriate one that I liked, and 
I couldn't. So Bookie shoved Gunnar's tome at me

22:18.738 --> 22:24.804
and said, here, why don't you do this one? So I did. 
And the more I read it, the more intrigued I got. I'm

22:29.288 --> 22:34.113
sure that Thorson was one of the primary 
motivating things. Anyone else? Well, there's

22:37.196 --> 22:39.118
quite a collection of people. I would like to think 
that Dennis Crisp influenced my thinking along

22:41.020 --> 22:45.365
that line. Although at that time he was not that 
actively involved in studies on larvae, he was in

22:46.646 --> 22:52.312
barnacles. And Harold Barnes, who I guess is the 
second best-known British scientist in the realm

22:52.332 --> 22:59.059
of Barnacle Research and with whom I attempted to 
work that year that I spent at Millport. He

23:06.142 --> 23:11.548
influenced my thinking for better or for worse.

